r perception of reality has inspired and influenced the most innovative historical accounts. Focusing on new research, this volume explores the history of non-elite populations in cities from Caracas to Vienna, and Paris to Belgrade. Narration is central to the theme of each contribution, whether as a means of description, a methodological approach, or basic story telling. This book brings together research that both asks classical socio-historical questions and takes narration seriously, engaging with novels, films, local history accounts, petitions to municipal authorities, and interviews with alternative cinema activists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCity and town life in literature. 0aCity and town life in motion pictures. 0aCity and town lifexHistoriography. 0aCommunity lifexHistoriography. 0aDiscourse analysis, Narrative. 0aMiddle classxHistoriography. 0aNarration (Rhetoric) 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aNarration. 0aPublic spacesxHistoriography. 0aWorking classxHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh1 aAlmandoz, Arturo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Matthew P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Matthew P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChristou, Anastasia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFischer-Nebmaier, Wladimir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer-Nebmaier, Wladimir, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohnston, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeutloff-Grandits, Carolin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcIvor, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 